<common-name datatype='string'>hisLGDCBHAFI</common-name>
<comment datatype='string'>The &lt;I&gt;hisLGDCBHAFI&lt;/i&gt; operon codes for the enzymes of the histidine
biosynthesis pathway. It is controlled by attenuation in response to
histidine availability. When histidine is abundant, the ribosome quickly
translates through a stretch of seven histidine codons in the &lt;i&gt;hisL&lt;/i&gt;
leader region, allowing formation of the transcriptional terminator between &lt;i&gt;hisL&lt;/i&gt;
and &lt;i&gt;hisG&lt;/i&gt;. In contrast, when histidine is not available, the
ribosome stalls within the leader region and the terminator will not form,
allowing transcription to continue [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/360215&quot;&gt;Di78&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6170941&quot;&gt;Verde81&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6166940&quot;&gt;Frunzio81&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
This operon appears to be positively regulated by a not-yet-characterized small protein that binds to the operator, altering the RNA secondary structure and affecting the attenuation of the operon [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/36920032&quot;&gt;Babina23&lt;/a&gt;].</comment>
